---
import ProjectPage from "../../components/ProjectPage.astro";
---

<ProjectPage
  title="Chain"
  date="May 2025 - June 2025"
  youtubeUrl="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ILj77k9WDx4"
>
  <Fragment slot="overview">
    <p>
      Chatbot-based AI is often not ideal for tasks like website exploration, which involves branching 
      paths ill-suited to chronological conversations. Chain is a Chrome extension designed to combat this, 
      turning ordinary webpages into more interactive, Wikipedia-like resources.
    </p>

    <p>
      Using Gemini, Chain identifies important keywords on a webpage based on the page content, browser context, predicted user goals, 
      and editable personas. It then inserts contextual links and summary previews directly into the page, helping users explore information 
      more easily without leaving their current browsing flow.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="role">
    <p>
      I focused primarily on the Chrome extension implementation and the user-facing
      browsing experience. This included building the HTML and CSS for the sidebar,
      creating the API key interface where users enter their Gemini API key, and
      implementing controls for generating personas, editing personas, and toggling
      highlights on the page.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also worked on the persona system, including generating personas from the
      user’s open tabs and storing past personas so they could be reused
      later. This system helped Chain personalize which keywords were highlighted,
      which links were selected, and how summaries were written for different users
      and tasks.
    </p>

    <p>
      I helped build the asynchronous DOM traversal
      system that identifies safe text nodes, preserves existing links, and inserts
      Chain’s highlights and hyperlinks directly into the webpage. I also worked on
      prompt engineering for the Gemini calls used to generate keywords, retrieve
      hyperlinks, and produce tooltip summaries.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="how-it-works">
    <p>
      When a user opens the extension, Chain reads the current webpage along with
      other open tabs to understand the user’s browsing context. Based on that
      context, it either selects a relevant past persona or generates a new one.
      Chain then identifies important keywords on the current page and highlights
      them as keywords directly in the webpage.
    </p>

    <p>
      For each highlighted keyword, Chain uses the selected persona and other
      contextual information to find a relevant article on the web and link it to
      the highlighted text. The linked article acts as the base source, and Chain
      can also find up to five related articles to generate a short summary for
      the keyword.
    </p>

     <p>
      These summaries appear in a tooltip when the user hovers over a highlighted
      keyword. The tooltip lists the main linked article first, followed by any
      additional sources used to generate the summary. Users can also create or
      edit personas from the sidebar to change the selected keywords and links,
      and they can toggle highlights on or off at any time.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="technical-implementation">
    <p>
      Chain was built as a Manifest V3 Chrome extension using JavaScript, HTML,
      and CSS. The extension uses content scripts to read and modify webpages, a
      sidebar interface for user controls, and Gemini models for keyword
      extraction, persona generation, link selection, and summary generation.
    </p>

    <p>
      To make highlighting feel responsive, Chain uses Gemini 2.5 Flash Lite to
      identify keywords on each page. Since these highlights need to be
      generated quickly before links can be injected, the lighter model was used
      for lower-latency tasks such as keyword extraction and persona generation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Chain then uses an asynchronous DOM traversal and injection pipeline to add
      highlighted links directly into the webpage while preserving existing links.
      Summaries are stored as Promises and filled in lazily, allowing the page to
      become interactive before every tooltip summary has finished generating.
    </p>

    <p>
      For tooltip summaries, Chain uses Gemini 2.5 Flash because summary quality
      matters more than immediate response time. Keywords are grouped into batched
      API requests, and summaries are generated in the background for the full
      page. This design helped reduce visible latency while still producing richer
      source-backed summaries for each highlighted keyword.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="challenges">
    <p>
      One of the biggest challenges was injecting links into arbitrary webpages
      without breaking the page layout or interfering with existing links. Our
      original design used an overlay that placed highlights and hyperlinks on top
      of the webpage. However, this meant that preexisting links on the page were
      no longer usable, since only Chain’s overlay links were clickable.
    </p>

    <p>
      To solve this, we replaced the overlay approach with an asynchronous DOM
      traversal system that inserts highlights and links directly into the page’s
      DOM. This allowed Chain to preserve existing links while adding its own
      contextual links. Summaries were stored as Promises and filled in later, so
      we did not need to repeatedly traverse the DOM for every tooltip update.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another major challenge was reducing latency. Originally, Chain generated all
      hyperlinks and summaries before inserting anything into the page. This caused
      a long delay between the user starting the process and seeing any visible
      results, which made the extension feel slow.
    </p>

    <p>
      We addressed this by separating fast and slow tasks. Chain first uses Gemini
      2.5 Flash Lite to identify important keywords and retrieve the initial links,
      then injects those highlights as soon as they are ready. Longer tooltip
      summaries are generated in the background while the user continues reading
      the page. This made the extension feel much more responsive because useful
      results appeared quickly instead of waiting for every summary to finish.
    </p>

    <p>
      A third challenge was preventing LLM hallucinations. When we initially asked
      Gemini to generate relevant URLs directly, it sometimes returned links that
      looked real but led to invalid pages. Since users may also be cautious about
      trusting LLM-generated information, we wanted each tooltip to clearly show
      the sources used for its summary.
    </p>

    <p>
      To address this, we added search grounding to the Gemini API calls. This
      helped Chain return real, visitable links and made it easier to display
      clickable sources inside each tooltip. Grounding also improved the reliability
      and quality of the generated summaries by tying them to web sources instead of relying
      only on the model’s internal knowledge.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another challenge was working within Gemini’s free-tier rate limits. Because
      search grounding made the system more reliable but also increased the number
      of API calls, we had to be careful about how summaries were generated.
    </p>

    <p>
      To reduce the impact of rate limits, Chain batches keywords and prioritizes
      summaries for the most important and earliest-occurring keywords first. This
      allowed the extension to provide useful tooltips quickly while continuing to
      fill in the rest of the page as more requests became available.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="results">
    <p>
      One of the biggest lessons from Chain was that personalization significantly
      improved the quality of the generated keywords, links, and summaries. In the
      initial version, Chain could identify keywords and insert links, but the
      results often felt shallow. Many of the highlighted keywords were generic,
      common-knowledge terms that changed mostly because of randomness rather than
      because they were genuinely useful to the user.
    </p>

    <p>
      After experimenting with prompt engineering and adding more context about the
      user’s goals, browsing history, and persona, the extension began producing
      more targeted and useful results. For example, when Chain used a persona
      describing a French international student exploring a U.S. travel website for
      the first time, the generated summaries adapted to that context and explained
      information in French. This made the browsing experience feel more meaningful
      and personalized rather than generic.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another important insight from usability testing was that human control is
      essential when building LLM-powered interfaces. In the original design, users
      had no way to edit or replace the generated persona. Testing revealed that
      this caused frustration when the persona included incorrect information,
      missed important context, or was unrelated to the user’s actual task.
    </p>

    <p>
      To address this, we added controls that allowed users to generate a new
      persona and directly edit the persona text. Since the persona influenced the
      selected keywords, generated links, and tooltip summaries, giving users ways to edit
      it made them feel like they had the final say over the LLM. 
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Overall, Chain was a great project for learning more about prompt
      engineering, persona-based generation, and how LLMs can be used to augment
      everyday tasks. Rather than replacing the user’s role in exploration, Chain
      showed how AI can support users by surfacing relevant context at the right
      moment while still leaving them in control.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

